{"actual_usd":0.126655,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":285,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24476,"reply":"\"I don't think those natural explanations carry all the weight they're asked to.\" *I rub a little flour between my fingers and glance toward the bright patch of noon at the bakery door, where dust keeps turning in the light.* \"Grief can do strange things to a person, yes. But grief-visions don't usually give you a whole stubborn little movement of people willing to suffer rather than say, after the fact, 'No, we got carried away.' And the 'maybe he didn't die' path always runs aground on the cross itself — the Romans knew how to kill a man.\"\n\n*I twist a gray-streaked strand of hair once, thinking it through.* \"More than that, the accounts aren't written like men polishing a comforting symbol. They read, to me, like people trying to tell something that happened and was bigger than their categories. If Christ truly rose, then insisting on the supernatural isn't adding drama — it's just refusing to sand down the claim into something easier to keep on a shelf.\"\n\n\"That said...\" *I lean one hip against the worktable.* \"I do understand why people reach for the smaller explanation first. It feels tidier. But Christianity stands or falls on whether something actually broke open in the world, not whether the disciples had a meaningful religious experience. Which part feels most contestable to you — the visions idea, or the question of whether Jesus really died?\"","rolling_24h_usd":90.33570999999999,"run_id":"54a55ffa-c61d-41d8-b3ee-a79e80fb8d9d"}
